
In-Class Activity: Risk Response Planning
Canada Life Acquisition of Santé Circle Health
ALY 6130 – Risk Management Analytics | Group 2
Doris Margaret Zotu-Osei, Abigail Dabanka-Frimpong, and Anita Atugbokoh

Instructions Recap
Using the risk heat map and the qualitative and quantitative risk assessment developed in our prior activities as a guide, this activity develops risk response plans for our top-priority critical risks. For each risk, we identified the applicable response strategy — avoidance, mitigation/reduction, transfer, or acceptance — and justified that choice based on the nature of the risk, its score, and the controls realistically available to Canada Life during the integration period.
Selected Top-Priority Critical Risks
From our 18-risk register, we selected the four highest-scoring risks for response planning: R-003 (cross-selling revenue synergy shortfall, score 20), R-001 (goodwill write-down, score 16), R-013 (legacy system incompatibility, score 16), and R-010 / R-017 (PHI data breach and Law 25/PIPEDA non-compliance, both score 15, treated together given their shared root cause). Each of these sits in the high-likelihood, high-impact zone of our heat map and represents the risks where Canada Life has the least room for a reactive approach.
Risk R-003: Cross-Selling Revenue Synergy Shortfall
R-003	Cross-selling revenue synergies fall short of projections	Score 20	HIGH	MITIGATE

Response Strategy: Mitigation / Reduction
We chose mitigation over acceptance because this is the highest-scoring risk in our entire register and the financial case for the acquisition depends directly on it. Avoidance is not realistic — Canada Life cannot back out of the synergy assumptions baked into the deal. Transfer is not applicable here since there is no third party to shift this kind of commercial execution risk to through insurance or contract. That leaves mitigation as the only strategy that genuinely reduces the probability of the synergy targets being missed, by actively driving broker adoption and client uptake rather than passively hoping the projections hold.
Response Action	Owner	Timeline	Success Measure
Launch broker incentive programme tied to Santé Circle cross-sell volume	Chief Revenue Officer	0–3 months	Broker adoption rate >38% by month 3
Build and deploy structured cross-sell playbook for client-facing teams	Chief Revenue Officer	0–2 months	Playbook used in >80% of client conversations
Run 90-day client outreach campaign targeting top group benefits accounts	Chief Revenue Officer	0–3 months	Client uptake rate ≥18% per campaign
Track synergy revenue against plan on CFO dashboard	CFO	Ongoing, monthly	Revenue ≥70% of Q1 target
Risk R-001: Goodwill Write-Down if Synergies Don't Materialise
R-001	Goodwill write-down required if synergies fail to materialise	Score 16	HIGH	MITIGATE

Response Strategy: Mitigation / Reduction
This risk is closely tied to R-003, since a goodwill impairment is really the accounting consequence of synergies and valuation assumptions not holding up. We selected mitigation rather than acceptance because the financial exposure is too large to simply absorb, and rather than transfer because impairment risk on an acquired business is not insurable in any meaningful way. An independent valuation and a phased earnout structure directly reduce the likelihood that Canada Life overpays relative to what Santé Circle Health actually delivers, which is the most effective lever available before the deal closes.
Response Action	Owner	Timeline	Success Measure
Commission independent third-party valuation of Santé Circle Health	CFO	Pre-close	Valuation variance from internal estimate <10%
Structure phased earnout tied to realised synergy milestones	CFO / Legal	Pre-close	Earnout terms signed before close
Maintain synergy tracking dashboard reviewed monthly by CFO	CFO	Ongoing, monthly	Variance to plan flagged within 30 days
Risk R-013: Legacy System Incompatibility
R-013	Legacy system incompatibility disrupts data exchange	Score 16	HIGH	MITIGATE

Response Strategy: Mitigation / Reduction
Avoidance would mean not integrating the two technology environments at all, which defeats the purpose of the acquisition, so that was ruled out. Acceptance was also ruled out given that system incompatibility is cited as one of the most common causes of M&A failure, and the impact — operational downtime affecting clinical service delivery — is too disruptive to simply tolerate. Mitigation through pre-close IT due diligence and a phased migration roadmap is the strategy that actually closes the architectural gap between Canada Life's enterprise systems and Santé Circle's boutique platforms before it can cause real disruption.
Response Action	Owner	Timeline	Success Measure
Conduct comprehensive pre-close IT due diligence on both platforms	CTO / IT PMO	Pre-close	Full system compatibility report delivered before close
Build API integration layer between Canada Life and Santé Circle systems	CTO / IT PMO	0–6 months	API coverage gap reduced to <10%
Execute phased migration roadmap with rollback capability	CTO / IT PMO	0–12 months	Unplanned downtime <4 hours/month
Run parallel processing period during cutover	COO / IT	3–6 months	Data exchange error rate <1%
Risk R-010 / R-017: PHI Data Breach and Law 25 / PIPEDA Non-Compliance
R-010/017	PHI data breach and regulatory non-compliance in health data handling	Score 15	HIGH	MITIGATE + TRANSFER

Response Strategy: Mitigation / Reduction, Supported by Transfer
This is the one risk in our top tier where we landed on a blended strategy rather than a single response. The core exposure — protecting personal health information during integration — has to be mitigated directly, because avoidance is impossible given that handling PHI is central to what Santé Circle Health does, and acceptance is unacceptable given that penalties under Quebec's Law 25 and PIPEDA can reach CAD $25 million or 4% of global revenue. At the same time, we recommend transferring a portion of the residual financial exposure through cyber liability insurance, since no combination of technical controls fully eliminates breach risk, and insurance is the appropriate tool for the exposure that remains after mitigation is applied.
Response Action	Owner	Timeline	Success Measure
Implement role-based access controls and AES-256 encryption across PHI systems	CISO	Pre-close to 0–3 months	100% of PHI systems covered by RBAC and encryption
Deploy 24/7 Security Operations Centre monitoring with annual penetration testing	CISO	0–3 months, then ongoing	Mean time to detect threat <2 hours
Complete mandatory Privacy Impact Assessments and Law 25/PIPEDA compliance audit	DPO / General Counsel	Pre-close	Zero unresolved critical audit findings at go-live
Secure or expand cyber liability insurance coverage for residual breach exposure	CFO / Legal	Pre-close	Coverage limit ≥ CAD $25M aligned to regulatory exposure
Reflection
Working through this activity as a group, the clearest takeaway was that mitigation dominates our response strategy across nearly every top-priority risk — which makes sense given that these are the risks Canada Life chose to take on by pursuing this acquisition in the first place. Avoidance was never realistic for any of the four risks, since avoiding them would mean not doing the deal at all. Acceptance was also ruled out everywhere except for risks scoring in the medium or low band, because the impact at this level is too significant to absorb without an active response. The one place we genuinely debated strategy was R-010/R-017, where the group agreed that pure mitigation wasn't enough on its own — no amount of access control and encryption brings breach probability to zero, so transferring the residual exposure through insurance felt like the responsible complement rather than a substitute for the technical controls.
